Introduction¶

In this project, we will analyse the dataset "No-show appointmennts". "This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Braazil". It is about people who scheduled a doctor appointment then they showed up or not depending on several criteria that we will try to find them out. The dataset contans 14 columns with relevant data that we will try to analyze to predict if a new patient will show up or not. The dataset header is very clear and no need to clarify the columns further. The No-show category is encoded to No/Yes. We will re-encode it later to show column with 1 for No(no-NoShow==Show) and 0(yes-NoShow=Did not show up) for Yes. This will make the analysis easier rahter than analysing two negative logics. Scholarship column "indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in The Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família"

During this dataset analysis, we will try to answer below questions:

  • Are same patients always showing up to their appointments?
  • Are there some patients who have never showed up to their appointments and others who have always showed up?
  • Age distribution for those who show up and who do not ((Minor-Major) or (age gap))
  • Does receiving SMS impacts the arrival of patients?
  • Is showing up higher with a specific gender?
  • Does the duration between the scheduling day and the appointment day impacts the rate of people showing up?
  • Do patients do not show up during specifc weekdays?
  • Do patients do not show up during some specific days?
  • Do patients enrolled in the scholarship have always showed up ?
  • Does having one of the symptoms(Hypertension, Diabetes, Alcholism or a special needs person) whill restrain the patients from showing up? Which symptom is a major factor?
  • Do some neighbourhood present a higher rate of people not showing up?

def pieChart(title,entry,labelsList,figsize):
    entry.plot(kind='pie',autopct='%1.1f%%', labels=labelsList,figsize=figsize)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show

Research Question 1¶

  • Are same patients always showing up to their appointments?
  • Are there some patients who have never showed up to their appointments and others who have always showed up?

Get the mean of Show per patient then draw a bar chart to check if there are some patients who have always show up and others who have never showed up to their appointments As we may need to use a bar chart later, let's create a fundction for it first of all.

In [46]:
def barChart(title, entry, figsize,x,y):
    entry.plot(kind='bar', figsize=figsize)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y)
    plt.show

In [48]:

    plt.show

Conclusions¶

  • Their are patients who show up always and others who have never showed up

  • Showing up depends on the patient age.Younger people tends to not to show up.

  • The longer the patients have to wait, the higher rate of them not showing up. Meanwhile, the patients who have to wait more than three months tend to show up more.

  • Patients take appointment during weekday, espeically on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. There are no spcial days of the calenday where all the patients did not show up.

  • Receiving SMS, Gender, Scholarship and special needs do not affect showing up

  • The majority of patients are not enrolled in the scholarship.

  • Patients do not shw up depending on the neighbourhood
    • </ul> To analyze data in a better way, we need to know how the appointments are being scheduled and patients data is being stored. We found a negative age value and several appointments dates set before the scheduling dates.

Limitations:¶

  • The data found in the dataset is corrupted. We found a negative age vaue and 34.9% of negative wait time entries which is considered a high rate especially that we needed to remove all these corrupted entries.
  • The middleAge category (between 18 and 40) are the least to show up for an appointments. It could be a work related constraint. If we found occupation related entries in the dataset, we could make a more precise analysis
  • The correlation between the dataset elements is very low. We cannot findout, using only correlation diagram and table, a direct relationship between No-Show and other entries
